flowRoot.flowPara: Software has proliferated in bioinformatics and so have the problems associated with it: missing or unobtainable code, difficult to install dependencies, unreproducible workflows, all with terrible user experiences. Moreover, the diversity of bioinformatic tools leads to the fact that many tools, which are made for the same purpose, differ in their interfaces. Interfaces of such tools are often not easy to understand and to use. text.tspan: Standardized bioinformatics tools using Docker containers
Peter Belmann, Michael Barton, Johannes Dröge, Albert Vilella

flowRoot.flowPara: Bioboxes are used in two projects:
CAMI Nucleotid.es
Both projects are evaluating bioinformatic tools
and demand the reproducibility of scientific
results. The effect of the Bioboxes
standardization is that a biobox tool build
by one project can be reused by another one.
Further, Bioboxes involves community by
providing a user, developer and contribution
guide.
Bioboxes are grouped in types:
-Assembler
-Assembler Evaluation
-Binning
-Binning Evaluation
-Profiling
-Profiling Evaluation

Each type has its own standardized input and output.The great value of Bioboxes is that the containers are interchangeable. Neither the input has to be adjusted nor another output format has to be expected, if using multiple Bioboxes of one type.

Docker is a technology for deploying applications inside software containers. A Docker container can be compared to a VM, but in contrast to a virtual machine, it does not include a separate operating system and, therefore, starts up lightning fast.

Bioboxes is a community standard using software containers like the below described Docker. The use of Docker makes the distribution and installation of software easy because all dependencies are inside the container. If this container works on one system, It will work on any other system with Docker installed. Furthermore, the standardized software interface makes the execution of a container easy and allows to use containers interchangeably. Consequently, instead of distributing the software to the users, a software container is provided that runs on any operating system.

The Bioboxes input must be described in a yaml file. A biobox.yaml provides always a version number and an array of arguments. For an assembler, a list of fastq entries must be provided as input. A fastq entry has always an unique id (test_reads), the fastq type (paired) and the path to the file inside the container (/bbx/input/reads.fq.gz).

In order to start a biobox, the docker run command must be specified. --volume allows to mount a directory inside the container. Bioboxes input must be mounted to /bbx/input together with biobox.yaml and the output directory to /bbx/output.
